    <!-- SECTION: PRINCIPLES (not pinned; fades in) -->
    <section id="pcl" class="border-t hairline">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 py-20">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-10 items-start">
          <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-4">
            <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-slateblue/90">[PRINCIPLES]</div>
            <h2 class="section-title mt-4 text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.01em]">
              PCL engineering posture
            </h2>
            <p class="mt-4 text-slateblue leading-relaxed measure">
              NADIR is record infrastructure. It is designed to be constrained by explicit policy scope, minimized to operational necessity, and protected against secondary-use drift.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-8">
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
              <div class="border hairline p-6 no-rounded reveal">
                <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[DATA MINIMIZATION]</div>
                <p class="mt-3 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                  NADIR captures only the metadata and decision-state context explicitly defined in the Policy Scope. Default posture is minimal capture, with opt-in expansion only where required by law, safety case, or operational governance.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="border hairline p-6 no-rounded reveal">
                <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[PURPOSE LIMITATION]</div>
                <p class="mt-3 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                  Artifacts generated for oversight and forensic audit are not designed for unauthorized surveillance, employee monitoring, or secondary model training. Operators retain configuration control and responsibility for lawful use.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="border hairline p-6 no-rounded reveal">
                <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[WEIGHT-NEUTRAL]</div>
                <p class="mt-3 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                  NADIR is designed not to ingest or retain model weights. Verification workflows are structured around integrity-bound artifacts rather than access to proprietary architectures or training data.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="border hairline p-6 no-rounded reveal">
                <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[CONSTRAINED DISCLOSURE]</div>
                <p class="mt-3 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                  Artifacts may be masked or redacted under policy rules while preserving cryptographic verifiability (e.g., stable hashes over canonical forms). The disclosure boundary is defined per deployment.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="mt-8 border hairline p-6 no-rounded reveal">
              <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[BOUNDARY]</div>
              <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                <li>NADIR does not adjudicate correctness, fairness, legality, or compliance outcomes.</li>
                <li>Authorized institutions and operators make determinations and retain responsibility for decisions.</li>
                <li>Policy Scope governs inclusion, exclusion, masking, retention, and access controls.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECTION: POLICY SCOPE PROTOCOL (table layout to avoid “same cards again”) -->
    <section class="border-t hairline">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-6 py-20">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-10">
          <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-4">
            <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-slateblue/90">[POLICY SCOPE]</div>
            <h2 class="section-title mt-4 text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.01em]">
              Operator-controlled scope
            </h2>
            <p class="mt-4 text-slateblue leading-relaxed measure">
              The Policy Scope is the primary civil liberties control surface. It defines what is recorded, how it is masked, where it resides, and who can verify it.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-8">
            <div class="border hairline no-rounded overflow-hidden reveal">
              <div class="px-6 py-4 border-b hairline bg-vellum">
                <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[SCOPE FIELDS]</div>
              </div>
              <div class="divide-y" style="border-color: rgba(71,85,105,0.22);">
                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Capture</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    Define which inference-time fields are eligible for artifact inclusion (inputs/outputs metadata, system parameters, integrity metadata) and which are excluded by default.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Masking</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    Apply explicit masking rules for sensitive fields (PII categories, secrets, regulated identifiers) while retaining verifiability through canonicalized hashing.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Retention</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    Set retention windows per artifact class (e.g., short for routine audit, longer for incident handling). Retention is operator-configured and jurisdiction-sensitive.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Residency</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    Prefer in-environment storage (client VPC / on-prem). NADIR is designed to avoid unnecessary data egress under constrained disclosure.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-12 px-6 py-4 gap-4">
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4 font-mono text-[11px] text-slateblue/90 uppercase tracking-[0.16em]">Access</div>
                  <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-8 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                    Role-based access for operators, auditors, and authorized institutions. Verification workflows should not require disclosure of model weights or proprietary architecture.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="mt-8 border hairline p-6 no-rounded reveal">
              <div class="font-mono text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-slateblue/90">[KEY CUSTODY]</div>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slateblue leading-relaxed">
                NADIR is designed for a non-custodial posture: signing keys are generated and retained within the operator’s controlled environment (HSM/KMS where available). NADIR does not require possession or transmission of private keys for verification workflows.
              </p>
            </div>

          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

